  "text": "Similar to Leszczuk's idea, [CITATION_1] we here propose a second-order difference method to reduce the overlapping between real cuts and various disturbances. Let ∆ 2 f k = ∆f k+1 −∆f k , then the ∆ 2 f k is a second-order difference. In the method, instead of ∆f k , ∆ 2 f k is compared to the threshold T cut . If ∆ 2 f k exceeds the threshold, a candidate cut is declared. As shown in the right plot of Fig. 2 , the values of disturbances can be successfully depressed. At the same time, the sharp peak of cut is preserved but in the form of a positive and a negative peak.",
